<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/33428641-andre-stackhouse"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1529692408i/33428641._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/33428641-andre-stackhouse">Andre Stackhouse</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Well I&apos;m not sure of anything specific, but I&apos;d say it qualifies as a modern fairy tale. Hansel and Gretel comes to mind. It&apos;s also sometimes compared<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Well I'm not sure of anything specific, but I'd say it qualifies as a modern fairy tale. Hansel and Gretel comes to mind. It's also sometimes compared to Coraline by Neil Gaimen, though that was a decade later. Coraline was influenced by Alice's Adventures in Wonderland, so I'd say it's fair to say there's a bit of that in there too. Anyway, this is all speculation about one of my favorite authors and books!<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
