        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer833268642" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7167789106919450226"><i>This was a place of illusions. Wouldn’t he be happier here if he just stopped questioning what was real and what wasn’t?</i><br/><br/>One of my favourite books of all time. If you loved Robert McCammon&apos;s Boy&apos;s Life, or Stephen King&apos;s IT, you should love this. It has the same feel, and Barker has crafted such a tight, scary, immersive story in The Thief of Always.<br/><br/>I should really read more Barker, he&apos;s the master of turning your spine icy-cold:<br/><i>She had a face like a rolled-up ball of cobwebs, from which her hair</i></span>
  <span id="freeText7167789106919450226" style="display:none"><i>This was a place of illusions. Wouldn’t he be happier here if he just stopped questioning what was real and what wasn’t?</i><br /><br />One of my favourite books of all time. If you loved Robert McCammon's Boy's Life, or Stephen King's IT, you should love this. It has the same feel, and Barker has crafted such a tight, scary, immersive story in The Thief of Always.<br /><br />I should really read more Barker, he's the master of turning your spine icy-cold:<br /><i>She had a face like a rolled-up ball of cobwebs, from which her hair, which could also have been spiders’ work, fell in wispy abundance.<br /><br />Hanging between the bare branches of the trees—was a moon as wide and as white as a dead man’s smile.</i><br /><br />I can't believe I rated this only four stars the first time I read it five years ago. It draws you in, creeps you out, and is short and punchy. Most of all, it's magical, and sad, and ramps up to a perfect ending that nails the books premise - be thankful for the time you have, don't wish it away. <br /><br /><i>“There has to be some sane explanation.” <br /><br />“There is,” said Harvey. “It was magic.”</i></span>
